entGrade\": 1, \"questionGrade\": 1}, {\"answer\": \"Security attacks are harmful actions security\\nmechanisms are methods used for protection and\\nsecurity service are security features in a system.\", \"feedback\": \"The student\'s answer is generally correct but lacks precision. The definitions provided are close but not as detailed as the model answer. For example, the student did not mention that mechanisms are the tools used to implement services, and services are the actual protections provided to the system. Slight improvements could be made to align more closely with the model answer. (Hybrid similarity: 0.57, Context match: 0.50)\", \"questionId\": \"3\", \"studentGrade\": 0.75, \"questionGrade\": 2}, {\"answer\": \"confusing mechanisms and service can cause\\nProblems in system design.\", \"feedback\": \"The student\'s answer is not relevant to the given questions and does not demonstrate any understanding of the provided textbook context or the topics discussed. (Hybrid similarity: 0.12, Context match: 0.17)\", \"questionId\": \"4.a\", \"studentGrade\": 0, \"questionGrade\": 0}, {\"answer\": \"Amechanism can be used\\nused in different ways.\", \"feedback\": \"The student\'s answer does not address the specific questions related to struct layout, offsets, and C promotion rules as described in the textbook context. The response is vague and does not provide any relevant technical details or correct answers. (Hybrid similarity: -0.01, Context match: -0.02)\", \"questionId\": \"4.b\", \"studentGrade\": 0, \"questionGrade\": 0}, {\"answer\": \"separating them helps understand security better\", \"feedback\": \"The student\'s answer is not relevant to the provided context. The context discusses struct layouts, offsets, and C programming promotion rules, while the answer talks about understanding security. This does not demonstrate any understanding of the given topics. (Hybrid similarity: 0.04, Context match: 0.03)\", \"questionId\": \"4.c\", \"studentGrade